sample.title: Will Elon Musk‚Äôs Trillion Dollar Pay Package Become The New Norm In The U.S.?
sample.description:
Since the late 20th century CEO pay has exploded, widening the divide between the ultra wealthy and working class Americans. Now, Tesla CEO Elon Musk could set a new standard in CEO pay packages, becoming the first trillionaire CEO after his record breaking pay package was approved in November 2025. Tesla is not alone in this, U.S. mega-cap CEOs like Apple's Tim Cook, Google's Sundar Pichai, and Amazon's Andy Jassy are also seeing their net worth skyrocket, as massive pay packages become the standard across S&P 500 companies. So what is behind these huge pay outs, how do these companies afford them, and is there a payoff or is it just luck?

sample.title: Family of man shot dead by federal agent in Minneapolis ask for 'truth' | BBC News
sample.description:
Federal immigration officers have shot and killed a man in Minneapolis, US, identified by local officials as 37-year-old Alex Pretti.
 
State and federal officials have provided conflicting accounts of the moments prior to Pretti's death, which comes less than three weeks after Renee Good was shot dead by an immigration agent in the city
 
Homeland Security Secretary Kristi Noem said an agent fired "defensive shots" after Pretti "reacted violently", while Minnesota Governor Tim Walz said federal authorities' accounts are "nonsense" and "lies".
 
Pretti, a US citizen and nurse, has been described as a "kind-hearted soul" by his parents; they call for the "truth" about their son.

Andy Burnham's bid to return as UK MP blocked | BBC News
sample.description:
Andy Burnham has been blocked from standing as a candidate for an upcoming parliamentary by-election in the UK by Labour's ruling body.

As a directly elected mayor, Burnham had to get approval from Labour's national executive committee, after he applied to be a candidate on Saturday.

Some NEC members were concerned about an expensive mayoral election to replace Burnham, and allies of Prime Minister Sir Keir Starmer feared he could mount a leadership challenge, should he return to Westminster.

The move is likely to infuriate Labour MPs and some ministers who said local party members should have had the option of choosing the Greater Manchester mayor as the candidate.
